
[1]invest

   INVEST', v.t. [L. investio; in and vestio, to clothe. See Vest.]

   1. To clothe; to dress; to put garments on; to array; usually and most
   correctly followed by with, before the thing put on; as, to invest one
   with a mantle or robe. In this sense, it is used chiefly in poetry and
   elevated prose, not in colloquial discourse.

   2. To clothe with office or authority; to place in possession of an
   office, rank or dignity; as, to invest a person with a civil office, or
   with an ecclesiastical dignity.

   3. To adorn; to grace; as, to invest with honor.

   4. To clothe; to surround; as, to be invested with light, splendor or
   glory.

   5. To confer; to give. [Little used.]

   6. To inclose; to surround; to block up, so as to intercept succors of
   men and provisions and prevent escape; to lay siege to; as, to invest a
   town.

   7. To clothe money in something permanent or less fleeting; as, to
   invest money in funded or bank stock; to invest it in lands or goods.
   In this application, it is always followed by in.
